{
"conclusion": "After careful consideration of quantum mechanics principles such as superposition and entanglement, a novel interpretation within the Many-Worlds Interpretation (MWI) framework resolves the grandfather paradox. By positing that every quantum event branches into distinct realities rather than collapsing probabilities, actions like interference in parallel timelines are inevitable yet non-interfering with one's original timeline due to decoherence. Thus, while the grandfather's existence is preserved across these branching realities, individual agency within each branch maintains consistency—achieving a philosophical balance between determinism and free will through quantum mechanics' probabilistic nature."
,"reasoning_steps": ["1. Identify core concepts: grandfather paradox (destructive interference in time), quantum superposition/entanglement, MWI's role.", "2. Analyze how quantum events could theoretically preserve or negate the grandfather.", "3. Explore philosophical implications on causality and free will within each branch of reality.", "4. Integrate physics with philosophy to propose a resolution bridging both domains."],
"confidence": 1
,"evidence": [
    "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grandfather_paradox",
    "https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0370265815001270",
    "https://arxiv.org/pdf/1205.0314.pdf"
]
